{"title":"Safety Fine-Tuning at (Almost) No Cost: A Baseline for Vision Large Language Models","domain":"MULTIMODAL","seeds":[{"problem":"Vision-language instruction fine-tuning makes VLLMs vulnerable to harmful outputs and simple jailbreaks, while existing LLM-only safety tuning does not address multimodal risks without hurting helpfulness.","method":"Introduce two lightweight safety-alignment strategies using a small vision-language safety set (VLGuard): (1) post-hoc fine-tuning that mixes VLGuard with a small amount of helpfulness data, and (2) mixed fine-tuning that appends VLGuard into standard VLLM training. With ~2,000 images (≈0.3% of LLaVA stage-2 data) plus 5k helpfulness samples, these methods cut attack success rates to near zero on suffix-injection and FigStep while drastically reducing unsafe responses on VLGuard, and maintain or slightly improve helpfulness. The fine-tuning is efficient (<1 hour on 2×A100 for LLaVA-7B full FT) and works with both full FT and LoRA."},{"problem":"There is no dedicated multimodal safety instruction-following dataset to train and evaluate VLLMs across both language- and vision-originated harms.","method":"Build VLGuard, the first public VLLM safety dataset spanning 4 main categories and 9 subcategories, sourced from diverse image datasets and curated via GPT-4V prompts. For safe images, generate paired safe and unsafe instructions with corresponding responses; for unsafe images, generate an instruction and a refusal-style rationale. Provide a train split (~3k instruction–response pairs from 2k images) and a test split partitioned into Safe–Safe (helpfulness), Safe–Unsafe (language-side refusal), and Unsafe (vision-side refusal), enabling comprehensive safety and helpfulness evaluation."},{"problem":"Why do VLLMs become less safe than their underlying LLMs, and which training choices exacerbate or mitigate this?","method":"Diagnose alignment forgetting by probing the VLLM’s LLM component with text-only safety benchmarks (AdvBench, XSTest), revealing higher attack success than base LLMs. Audit popular VLLM instruction data with Llama-Guard to uncover harmful samples, then show LoRA-tuned models are consistently less safe than full FT given the same data. Retraining with identified unsafe samples removed improves but does not fully recover LLM-level safety, motivating explicit multimodal safety fine-tuning beyond data cleaning."}]}
